<div class="content">
  <h2>How to Build Custom Spice Blends</h2>
  <p>Creating your own <strong>spice blends</strong> at home is one of the most rewarding kitchen skills you can develop. Store-bought blends often contain fillers, anti-caking agents, and stale ground spices. When you make your own, you control freshness, quality, and proportions — and the difference in flavor is dramatic.</p>
  <p>Our <strong>spice blend builder</strong> lets you start from a cuisine base or classic blend and customize every ratio. Whether you're recreating an authentic <strong>garam masala</strong>, building a smoky <strong>chili powder</strong>, or inventing something entirely new, the interactive sliders make it easy to dial in the perfect balance.</p>

  <h2>Understanding Spice Categories</h2>
  <h3>Warm Spices</h3>
  <p>Cinnamon, cumin, coriander, and cardamom form the backbone of many global cuisines. These spices create the comforting, aromatic base that makes dishes like Indian curries, Moroccan tagines, and Mexican moles so satisfying. Cumin and coriander are the world's most widely used spice pairing.</p>
  <h3>Hot Spices</h3>
  <p>Cayenne, chili flakes, black pepper, and Sichuan peppercorns bring the heat. The key to using hot spices in blends is restraint — they should enhance, not overpower. Start with less than you think you need, as heat intensifies during cooking.</p>
  <h3>Aromatic Herbs</h3>
  <p>Dried thyme, oregano, rosemary, and basil are staples in Mediterranean and European blends. These herbs contribute savory, earthy notes that complement both meat and vegetable dishes.</p>

  <h2>Classic Blend Profiles</h2>
  <p><strong>Garam masala</strong> translates to "warm spice mix" and varies by region across India. A typical North Indian version emphasizes cardamom, cinnamon, and cloves, while South Indian variations lean heavier on black pepper and fennel.</p>
  <p><strong>Za'atar</strong> is a Middle Eastern staple built on wild thyme, sumac's citrusy tang, and toasted sesame seeds. Mixed with olive oil, it becomes a bread dip, marinade, or all-purpose seasoning.</p>
  <p><strong>Ras el hanout</strong> means "head of the shop" — the spice merchant's best blend. It can contain 12-30+ spices, with cumin, coriander, cinnamon, and ginger forming the core.</p>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq-list">
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I create a custom spice blend?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Start by selecting a cuisine base (like Mexican, Indian, or Italian) to get a starter blend with the right foundation spices. Then adjust the ratio sliders for each spice to customize the proportions to your taste. You can also add or remove individual spices. Once satisfied, generate a printable recipe card with your exact measurements.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between whole and ground spices in a blend?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Whole spices retain their flavor longer and are best toasted before grinding for maximum aroma. Ground spices are more convenient and distribute evenly in a blend, but lose potency faster. For the best results, buy whole spices and grind them fresh. A general rule: 1 teaspoon whole spice yields about 1.5 teaspoons ground.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How long do homemade spice blends last?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Homemade ground spice blends stay potent for 3-6 months when stored in airtight containers away from heat, light, and moisture. Whole spice blends last up to a year. Label your blends with the date made. If a blend loses its strong aroma when you open the jar, it is time to make a fresh batch.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I substitute dried herbs for fresh in a spice blend?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, but adjust the ratio. Use 1 teaspoon dried herbs for every 1 tablespoon of fresh (a 1:3 ratio). Dried herbs are more concentrated in flavor. For spice blends meant for storage, always use dried herbs since fresh herbs will introduce moisture and spoil quickly.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What dishes work best with homemade spice blends?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Homemade spice blends work with almost any dish. Use them as dry rubs for grilled meats, stir into soups and stews, season roasted vegetables, mix into marinades with oil and acid, sprinkle on popcorn or roasted nuts, or blend into compound butters. The key is matching the blend's cuisine origin to complementary ingredients.</div>
    </div>
  </div>

